\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: GMRES (20 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From class, the GMRES algorithm iteratively builds up an orthonormal basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{n}$
\end_inset

 for the Krylov space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}_{n}=\span{b,Ab,\ldots,A^{n-1}b}$
\end_inset

 and then uses this basis to solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{x\in\mathcal{K}_{n}}\Vert Ax-b\Vert_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We normally assume that each iteration 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gives us a linearly independent vector, i.e.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n}b$
\end_inset

 is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 What happens if this is false, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n}b\in\mathcal{K}_{n}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

breakdown
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)? Show that in the (unlikely) event that this occurs, it is a 
\emph on
good
\emph default
 thing, not a bad thing, for solving 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (which you can assume to have distinct eigenvalues and hence be diagonalizable)
, how would you (theoretically) construct a 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 such that breakdown occurs after 
\begin_inset Formula $n<m$
\end_inset

 steps (in exact arithmetic)?
\end_layout

