\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: Conditioning (20 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following parts can be solved 
\emph on
independently
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix (of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n<m$
\end_inset

).
 In some applications, only certain elements 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C=(A^{*}A)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are required.
 If you are given a few desired 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, outline an efficient, well-conditioned algorithm to compute those 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 (You can use as subroutines any of the algorithms described in class...you
 need not reproduce their details here.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compare the condition numbers of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=Ax$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(A)=Ax$
\end_inset

 (for 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathbb{C}^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{C}^{n}$
\end_inset

), using the 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 norm for vectors and a 
\emph on
Frobenius
\emph default
 norm for matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Recall that, for a differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z)$
\end_inset

 mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathbb{C}^{p}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z)\in\mathbb{C}^{q}$
\end_inset

, the condition number is 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(z)=\frac{\Vert J\Vert}{\Vert g(z)\Vert/\Vert z\Vert}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert J\Vert$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
induced
\emph default
 norm (
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{z\neq0}\frac{\Vert Jz\Vert}{\Vert z\Vert}$
\end_inset

) of the Jacobian matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{ij}=\frac{\partial g_{i}}{\partial z_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that, for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(A)=Ax$
\end_inset

, the inputs live in an 
\begin_inset Formula $mn$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector space so 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times(mn)$
\end_inset

 and you will have to think carefully about what 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Jz$
\end_inset

 should mean.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3: QR updating (20 points).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose you are given the QR factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $A=QR$
\end_inset

 of an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n<m$
\end_inset

).
 Describe an efficient 
\begin_inset Formula $O(m^{2}+n^{2})=O(m^{2})$
\end_inset

 algorithm to compute the QR factorization of a rank-1 update to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, that is to factorize 
\begin_inset Formula $A+uv^{*}=Q'R'$
\end_inset

 for some vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\mathbb{C}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathbb{C}^{n}$
\end_inset

, following these steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q'R'=Q(R+zv^{*})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 that can be computed in 
\begin_inset Formula $O(m^{2})$
\end_inset

 operations.
 Therefore, we just need to find a unitary matrix that (acting on the left)
 re-triangularizes 
\begin_inset Formula $R+zv^{*}$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q'$
\end_inset

, which may be stored implicitly in terms of a sequence of rotations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every column of 
\begin_inset Formula $zv^{*}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the same vector 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Using this fact, explain how we can apply Givens rotations (from the bottom
 row to the top) which rotate 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 into a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}$
\end_inset

, in order to convert 
\begin_inset Formula $R+zv^{*}$
\end_inset

 into 
\series bold
upper-Hessenberg
\series default
 form using 
\begin_inset Formula $O(m+n^{2})$
\end_inset

 operations.
 Recall from homework that a Givens rotation is a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix that rotates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
a\\
b
\end{array}\right)\to\left(\begin{array}{c}
\#\\
0
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
From the upper-Hessenberg form in the previous part, explain how we can
 unitarily convert back to upper-triangular form in 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n^{2})$
\end_inset

 operations.
\end_layout

